<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">
Medium sized species with peculiar male genitalia (Fig. 2), see also (
<bibRefCitation author="Podenas, S." journalOrPublisher="Spausdino Vilniaus Universiteto Leidukla, Vilnius" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" title="Identification keys for Limoniinae (Diptera, Limoniidae) of Mongolia and adjacent territories" year="2007">Podenas and Gelhaus 2007</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 51)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">
Palaearctic and Oriental regions (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">Oosterbroek 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Karelian record is the northernmost one. Closest locations are in Poland, Lithuania and Moscow province in Russia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="22175">
Saproxylic species. Larvae develop under the bark of various trees (
<bibRefCitation author="Krivosheina, N. P." journalOrPublisher="Entomological Review" pageId="0" pageNumber="22175" pagination="135 - 140" title="On the larval morphology and ecology of the limoniid Microlimoniamachidai (Diptera, Limoniidae)" volume="90" year="2010">Krivosheina 2010</bibRefCitation>
). This species was collected from a wind-broken aspen, colonised by 13 species of macrofungi (Table 1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
